></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-introductory-tutorial/">Bodysuit with Corset Cups <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="24"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-measurement/">Party Dress <span>(17)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#544">Transparent corsets  <span>(4)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="25"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-cutting-a-mock-up/">Corset with Drapery <span>(20)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="26"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-and-the-throw-over-sewing-technique/">Corset with Integral Straps <span>(27)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="34"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model/">Corset with 3-Part Cups <span>(22)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="76"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-getting-acquainted-with-the-model-5/">Corset with a Fancy Cut-Out <span>(22)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#3082">Decoration Techniques  <span>(9)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="83"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials/">Rhinestones Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="84"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-glue-on-half-pearls/">Additional Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="85"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-thick-decoration-element/">Thick Decoration Elements <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="86"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-decoration-materials-2/">Wedding Dress Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="87"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-types-of-sequins/">Sequins Decoration <span>(11)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="105"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-marking-the-borders-of-the-decoration/">Casual Garment Decoration <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="106"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/epaulettes-function-and-materials/">Epaulettes <span>(8)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="127"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tambour-or-luneville-embroidery-part-1/">Tambour or Luneville Embroidery <span>(5)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="128"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/the-button-loop-closure-part-1/">The Button Loop Closure <span>(2)</span></a></li></ul></li><li class="active">					<a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/categories/#4289">Fancy Dresses for Girls  <span>(5)</span></a><ul class="list-unstyled"><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="118"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/childrens-body-proportions/">The Law of Proportions in Children's Wear <span>(3)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="117"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-for-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 3 Years Old Girl <span>(9)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="119"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress/">Fancy Dress for 6 Years Old Girl <span>(16)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="120"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-style-with-respect-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 9 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li><li><a href="javascript:void(0)" class="nav-sub first blank" data-catid="135"><i class="fa fa-my-menu"></i></a> <a class="second" href="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-1-choosing-a-suitable-dress-with-regard-to-the-childs-body-proportions/">Fancy Dress for 12 Years Old Girl <span>(14)</span></a></li></ul></li>		</ul></div></div>													<div class="lesson-tab" role="tabpanel">				  <!-- Nav tabs -->				  <ul class="nav nav-tabs" role="tablist">					<li role="presentation" class="active"><a href="#about" aria-controls="about" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Course details</a></li>																		<li role="presentation"><a href="#transcript" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Transcript</a></li>														<li role="presentation"><a href="#pattern" aria-controls="pattern" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Pattern</a></li>					<li role="presentation"><a href="#diploma" aria-controls="transcript" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">Diploma</a></li>						<li role="presentation"><a class="faq-tab blank" href="#faq" aria-controls="faq" role="tab" data-toggle="tab">FAQs</a></li>				  </ul>				  <!-- Tab panes -->				  <div class="tab-content">				  																									<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane active" id="about">											<div class="dark-get-started margin-0">																																											<p><strong><em>Dressmaker’s Treasury&nbsp;</em></strong><strong>is a collection of key tools and skills which every dressmaker needs for successful work.</strong></p><p><strong>I am offering you a great instrument to help you acquire more confidence for fulfilling your creative projects!&nbsp;</strong>You will no longer have any fear of complex sophisticated garments! You will learn to work with mock-ups, make crinolines of non-standard shapes, and sew various kinds of fabric cases for petticoats to enhance the fullness of the main skirt.</p><p><strong>Our main goal at the Corset Academy&nbsp;</strong>is to teach you how to sew wedding and evening garments. And I want you to be able to sew a high-quality garment within a relatively short time.</p><p><strong>I don’t want you to spend lots of time on doing complicated calculations and making basic skirt patterns!</strong></p><p><strong>All necessary materials are included in the course:</strong></p><ul><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in the actual size (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Patterns of four silhouette skirts in half the actual size for sewing mock-ups and designing new skirt models (PDF);</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculation of all parameters required for cutting a trapeze-shaped skirt, a half-circle skirt, and a full-sweep skirt (HTML). These tables contain 18 tabs for calculating necessary parameters for the mentioned types of skirts, horizontal and vertical ruffles, falbalas, and the elastic waistband skirt.</h4></li><li><h4>Three tables for AUTOMATIC calculations with fixed parameters for the trapeze-shaped skirt, the half-circle skirt, and the full-sweep skirt (HTML);</h4></li></ul><h4>Fixed parameters (i.e. measurements) allow you to quickly calculate necessary data for cutting ruffles and falbalas for a skirt of a certain size: consumption of main fabric, lining fabric, decorative materials, etc.</h4><p><strong>Our new course&nbsp;<em>Dressmaker’s Treasury. Wedding Skirts and Petticoats&nbsp;</em>is a collection of important methods and skills which every dressmaker must know in order to achieve good results. It will be equally helpful for beginners and for experienced professionals!</strong></p><p><strong>Every professional dressmaker knows that sewing complex wedding skirts&nbsp;</strong>is not just about sewing together kilometers of fabric. The key thing is correct calculations and your ability to “foresee” the final results and related fabric consumption well before you start cutting and sewing.</p><p>I would also like to emphasize that the skirt from this course is merely a foundation for your own masterpieces. Let your creativity bloom!</p><p><strong>The course&nbsp;is&nbsp;useful both to beginner dressmakers, as well as experienced professionals.</strong></p><p><strong>Enjoy it!</strong></p><p><strong>Author:</strong>&nbsp;Tatiana Kozorovitsky</p><p><strong>Total length:</strong>&nbsp;6h 12m</p>												</div>						</div>										<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="transcript">						<div class="overlay"></div>						<!-- BEGIN Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Article --><div itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Article"><!-- Scope BEGIN: Organization --><span itemprop="publisher" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Organization"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="logo" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="name" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="text" content="Corset Academy logo"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="https://www.facebook.com/corsetacademy"></span> <!-- Scope END: Organization --><!-- Scope BEGIN: Person --><span itemprop="author" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/Person"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tatiana Kozorovitsky"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/uploads/MVI_3285.MOV.00_00_31_09.Still001-128x128.jpg"><meta itemprop="width" content="128"><meta itemprop="height" content="128"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/jpeg"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/author/infocorsetacademy-net/"><meta itemprop="sameAs" content="http://www.corsetacademy.net"></span> <!-- Scope END: Person --><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-34-calculating-horizontal-ruffles-for-the-petticoat/"><meta itemprop="mainEntityOfPage" content="https://corsetacademy.net/tutorial-34-calculating-horizontal-ruffles-for-the-petticoat/"><meta itemprop="datePublished" content="2018-05-08T18:26:53+00:00"><meta itemprop="dateModified" content="2018-05-08T18:26:53+00:00"><meta itemprop="copyrightYear" content="2018"><meta itemprop="inLanguage" content="en_US"><meta itemprop="name" content="Tutorial 34. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Petticoat."><meta itemprop="headline" content="Tutorial 34. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Petticoat."><meta itemprop="description" content="This tutorial will be dedicated to calculating horizontal ruffles for petticoats and their fabric casings. Such horizontal ruffles are always calculated"><meta itemprop="articleSection" content="Wedding Skirts and Petticoats. Practical Part."><meta itemprop="keywords" content="wedding skirts and petticoats. practical part., video"><!-- Scope BEGIN: ImageObject --><span itemprop="image" itemscope="" itemtype="http://schema.org/ImageObject"><meta itemprop="url" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="contentUrl" content="https://corsetacademy.net/wp-content/themes/corset/img/logo.png"><meta itemprop="width" content="303"><meta itemprop="height" content="49"><meta itemprop="encodingFormat" content="image/png"></span> <!-- Scope END: ImageObject --><div itemprop="articleBody"><h1>Tutorial 34. Calculating Horizontal Ruffles for the Petticoat.</h1><p><strong>This tutorial will be dedicated to calculating horizontal ruffles for petticoats and their fabric casings. </strong>Such horizontal ruffles are always calculated the same way regardless of what table you choose.</p><p>Considering this, let us use the already familiar Table for <strong>Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length. </strong></p><p><strong>First of all, let us see how to calculate ruffles for petticoats with hoops. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image031.jpg" alt="goldub-629"></p><p><strong>To make things easier, let us calculate them for a petticoat with a 270cm long bottom hoop (i.e. the same kind as was used for the previous examples). </strong>We have already figured out how to divide it in gores and now let us see how we can calculate ruffle parameters to make it fuller. If you are not going to put a fabric casing over your petticoat (regardless of whether it is a ready-made or a hand-made one), then you must put ruffles on the petticoat before inserting the hoops in the tunnels.</p><p><strong>Open the Table for Calculating a Skirt Based on Hem Length and go to the Horizontal Ruffles tab. </strong></p><p><strong>I put the same initial parameters in the table (red arrows): </strong></p><p>- Waist Circumference – 80cm;</p><p>- Front, Side, and Back Petticoat Length – 100cm;</p><p>- Desired Sector Angle – 109 degrees. This is enough for a bottom hoop with a length of 270cm.</p><p>- Waist Gathering Ratio – we will keep it at 1. I assume the calculated biggest possible hip circumference is greater than our client’s actual hip circumference so there is no need in additional gathering along the waistline.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image033.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The programme has instantly calculated all necessary radii (see the blue arrows). </strong>They will be particularly handy if you are going to cut a short skirt.</p><p>It is more fabric-efficient to cut long skirts in gores though.</p><p><strong>So, instead of looking at the suggested radii, let us look at the parts of the table which show the calculated key parameters of our horizontal ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>Let us set the additional parameters first: </strong></p><p>- Desired Number of Ruffles - 5;</p><p>- Ruffles Overlap – 3cm.</p><p><strong>Ruffles overlap </strong>is the value (a) by which the top ruffle overlays the previously attached bottom ruffle, i.e. the distance between the sewing edge of the bottom ruffle and the hem line of the top ruffle. Ruffle overlap is estimated based solely on your own criteria and the style of petticoat.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image034.jpg" alt="goldub-632"></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image036.jpg" alt=""></p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio - 4.</p><p>Ruffles are usually used to make the petticoat fuller. <strong>The gathering ratio depends directly on the stiffness of ruffle fabric. </strong></p><p>The softer it is, the greater the gathering ratio should be.</p><p><strong>It can be as much as 10, for example, for ruffles made of soft tulle. </strong>In other words, you can gather soft tulle down to 1/10 of its initial length.</p><p><strong>High- and medium-density mesh fabric is always gathered depending on the situation, </strong>i.e. after preliminary testing. In the case of such materials, <strong>the gathering ratio usually varies between 2 and 5. </strong>The thicker the ruffle is gathered, the more it sticks out making the petticoat fuller in the corresponding area.</p><p>- Width of Ruffles Fabric – 140cm.</p><p><strong>It is very important to use the correct width of fabric for cutting the ruffles. </strong>Fabric consumption depends on this value.</p><p><strong>The programme will automatically divide the full skirt length in equal sections depending on the entered number of ruffles and their overlap. </strong></p><p><strong>As the result, you will get the following parameters: </strong></p><p>- Ruffle Strip Width (Seam Allowances Included) – 24.8cm;</p><p>- Finished Ruffle Width – 22.4cm. This value gives you a better understanding of what the ruffle will look like when finished.</p><p>- Intervals – 19.4cm. It is the distance between the sewing edges of two ruffles (X).</p><p><strong>You will also find:</strong></p><p>- Total Fabric Consumption for All Ruffles – 5.5m or 550cm.</p><p><strong>As well as, fabric consumption per piece: </strong></p><p>- Fabric Consumption for Skirt Ruffles (train excluded) – 5.5m;</p><p>- Fabric Consumption for Train Ruffles (if applicable) – 0m.</p><p><strong>Moreover, you will get the following highly useful parameters: </strong></p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of All Skirt Ruffles – 7.7m;</p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of All Train Ruffles – 0m;</p><p>- And Total Sewing Edge Length of All Ruffles (Skirt and Train) – 7.7m.</p><p><strong>These aggregate sewing edge lengths will come in handy if you, for example, decide to use flounces instead of ruffles. </strong></p><p>You need to know the aggregate sewing edge length of ruffles in order to calculate the required number of ruffles and related fabric consumption.</p><p><strong>Open the Ruffles tab of the same table and put the necessary parameters in the boxes:</strong></p><p>- Total Sewing Edge Length of All Ruffles (train included) – 7.7m;</p><p>- Width of Fabric – 150cm;</p><p>- And existing ruffle parameters.</p><p><strong>The table offers us the following results:</strong></p><p>- Number of Ruffles – 16;</p><p>- Total Fabric Consumption for All Ruffles – 1.8m.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image038.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>If there were a train, </strong>the table would offer us a separately calculated number of ruffles for the train itself in correspondence with its length and the resulting distance between the sewing edges of ruffles (x). This automatically calculated distance (x) will be preserved on the train.</p><p><strong>Let us take a new example and change the existing back seam length to account for the train. Let it be 140cm. This will give us the following results: </strong></p><p>- Number of Train Ruffles – 3.</p><p><strong>This will naturally affect the fabric consumption and the sewing edge length, too. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image040.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>These sewing edges or sewing lines fully coincide with the guidelines for hoop tunnels on the petticoat in both what regards their position and their length. </strong>The table makes it clear how long each petticoat hoop is supposed to be. The hoops will be positioned at equal intervals (x).</p><p><strong>The total sewing edge length also shows you how much hoop steel you need to buy for your petticoat. </strong></p><p><strong>There are some important options for using this particular table, and it is better to demonstrate them using certain examples. Suppose, for example, that I want to have only three ruffles on my petticoat. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image041.jpg" alt="goldub-636"></p><p><strong>I need to put relevant date in the table to calculate the parameters of these ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>Suppose I want each of these three bottom ruffles to have a width of about 25cm. </strong></p><p><strong>Why am I saying “about”? </strong></p><p><strong>The thing is </strong>that the programme is going to suggest the best ruffle width depending on other selected parameters.</p><p><strong>And namely: </strong>I want to put the ruffles on the petticoat with 5cm overlaps&nbsp; and keep their widths within the bounds of 25cm, which means there should be about 20cm between their sewing lines or between the three bottom hoops.</p><p><strong>By doing calculations, I want to determine how much fabric I will need for three bottom ruffles with the described parameters. </strong></p><p><strong>I open the Horizontal Ruffles tab and put the key skirt parameters in the corresponding boxes. </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image043.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>I start from the values which will stay constant: </strong></p><p>- Ruffles Overlap – 5cm,</p><p>- Ruffle Gathering Ratio – 3.</p><p>I have chosen this gathering ratio because I will cut these ruffles from hard mesh fabric.</p><p>- Width of Ruffle Fabric – 150cm.</p><p><strong>In order to solve the task, I need to first of all select a suitable number of ruffles to get intervals of about 20cm between them. </strong></p><p>- I find and select the corresponding number of ruffles for a skirt without train – 5.</p><p><strong>Let us see what the table has calculated in this case: </strong></p><p>- Intervals – 19cm,</p><p>- Finished Ruffle Width – 24cm.</p><p><strong>This is exactly what I need! </strong></p><p><strong>But the programme has done these calculations for five ruffles which start from the waistline. </strong></p><p><strong>Each ruffle </strong>has a width of 24cm. The ruffles are positioned with 5cm overlaps and the distances between their sewing lines are 19cm.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image044.jpg" alt="goldub-638"></p><p><strong>And we only want to know fabric consumption for the three bottom ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong>I have provided for this option in the tables. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image046.jpg" alt=""></strong></p><p><strong>Scroll down until you see a picture of a skirt with two bottom ruffles and you will see calculated ruffle fabric consumption for the cases when their number is fewer than given initially. </strong></p><p><strong>The ruffles are numbered from up to down, i.e. from waist to hem line. </strong></p><p>I initially selected five ruffles to get the desired width and intervals.</p><p><strong>Here is what we read in the table:</strong></p><p>- Fabric consumption starting from the second ruffle is 3.7m. This is how much fabric you need for the four remaining ruffles if you exclude the first one (the one at the very top).</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image047.jpg" alt="goldub-641"></p><p><strong>What we need is the next line: </strong></p><p><strong>- Fabric consumption starting from the third ruffle is 2.9m. </strong></p><p><strong>This is how much fabric we need for the three bottom ruffles. </strong></p><p><strong><br><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image048.jpg" alt="goldub-642"></strong></p><p><strong>Once you understand this principle, you can easily calculate fabric consumption for any number of ruffles </strong>for a petticoat or a skirt, both for the case when the full garment is covered by them and when you only need to put several ruffles down the bottom.</p><p><strong>Let me remind you </strong>that you can get the desired ruffle width and intervals by changing the total number of ruffles on the skirt.</p><p><strong>For example, suppose you want to put the same three ruffles down the bottom of your skirt but you want to make them narrower (say, 10cm) and put them at 15cm intervals. </strong>In this case, you will select a suitable number of ruffles in the top part of the table so that the calculated width of ruffle and intervals between ruffles are close to what you want to achieve. And then you will take away all top ruffles leaving only the desired number (the three bottom ruffles in our case). The task will be solved.</p><p><strong>So we will need 290cm of 150cm-wide fabric in order to make three 24cm-wide ruffles gathered to 1/3 of their initial length and put at 19cm intervals with 5cm overlaps. </strong></p><p><strong>The table has also calculated the following: </strong></p><p>- Fabric consumption starting from the fourth ruffle is 2.1m. This is how much fabric you would need for the two bottom ruffles.</p><p>- And, finally, fabric consumption starting from the fifth ruffle is 1.1m. This is how much fabric you would need for one ruffle at the very bottom of your skirt or petticoat.</p><p><strong>NB: please pay attention to all warnings, illustrations, and tips given in the table! </strong></p><p><strong>Follow this instruction! It is vital! Set Back Skirt Length as equal to Front Skirt Length! Otherwise the table will calculate ruffle parameters for a skirt with a train!</strong></p><p><strong>In addition, you will find calculated parameters of each separate ruffle in the right part of our table titled “Calculating Ruffle Lengths for Skirt without Train.” </strong></p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image050.jpg" alt=""></p><p><strong>The table gives you: </strong></p><p>- The initial length of the strip of fabric with regard to the gathering ratio,</p><p>- The sewing edge length of the resulting gathered ruffle,</p><p>- And the distance from the waistline to the sewing edge of the ruffle. This parameter (y) will allow you to double-check the position of any ruffle on the skirt / petticoat.</p><p><strong>Let us return to our task. </strong></p><p><strong>We have figured </strong>that we leave only three bottom ruffles (3, 4, and 5) out of the initial five ruffles selected in the table. Ruffles 1 and 2 are excluded in our case.</p><p><img class="img-responsive center-block" src="https://corsetacademy.s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/Dressmaker_Essential_Skirts/Transcripts/Tutorial%2034.files/image051.jpg" alt="goldub-644"></p><p><strong>Let us take ruffle 3. </strong>It is made from a 460cm long strip of fabric and its sewing edge is 150cm long. As you understand, this 150cm is simultaneously the length of the petticoat hoop positioned at the same level (if you are making a petticoat). There is 38cm between the sewing edge of this ruffle and the waistline. This shows us where on the petticoat the hoops or the ruffles will start. And then they will continue downwards at 19cm intervals.</p><p><strong>Next comes ruffle 4. </strong>Considering the gathering ratio, it needs to be made from a longer strip of fabric –570cm. The sewing edge (and the corresponding hoop) is 190cm long. And this ruffle (or hoop tunnel) will be positioned 57cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>The last ruffle is ruffle 5. </strong>It is made from a 670cm long strip of fabric, its sewing edge is 220cm long, and it is positioned 76cm below waistline.</p><p><strong>Since we know that each ruffle has a width of 24cm, there will be 100cm between the bottom edge of the last ruffle (ruffle 5) and the waistline, which is just what we want. </strong></p></div> <!-- Itemprop END: articleBody --></div> <!-- Scope END: Article --><!-- END Schema.org microdata added by the Add-Meta-Tags WordPress plugin --> 					</div>															<div role="tabpanel" class="tab-pane" id="pattern">						<h3>Automatic&nbsp;Calculation 